# ── THE ACTUAL CATEGORY LEADERS ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Not on the original review list, and found by the scan's own --discover pass on
# 2026-07-14 — which is the argument for automating discovery. These three are
# local-first personal knowledge bases with ~126k stars between them. They are
# Reckons.AI's category, and we were not looking at them.
#
# All three are AGPL-3.0. Reckons.AI is MIT. That means COPY NOTHING: pulling AGPL
# code into an MIT project forces AGPL onto the whole of Reckons.AI. Read them,
# learn from them, take no expression. The license gate exists for exactly this.

kb:comp-logseq rdf:type        ktype:Competitor ;
               rdfs:label   "Logseq" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:competitive-landscape ;
               hnav:order   10 ;
               kpred:repo-url     "https://github.com/logseq/logseq" ;
               kpred:license      "AGPL-3.0" ;
               kpred:copy-permitted "NO — AGPL-3.0 is copyleft and Reckons.AI is MIT. Copying would force AGPL-3.0 on the whole project. Ideas only." ;
               kpred:stars        43855 ;
               kpred:last-push    "2026-07-14"^^xsd:date ;
               kpred:description  "Privacy-first, open-source platform for knowledge management. Outliner-based, local files (markdown/org), bidirectional links, an in-app query language over the block graph." ;
               kpred:closest-to   kb:core-product ;
               kpred:honest-note  "This is the closest thing to a direct competitor in the whole graph and it was not on the list we were asked to review. Its local-first commitment matches ours and its user base dwarfs ours." ;
               kpred:differs-from "Logseq's graph is a BACKLINK graph over documents — the nodes are pages and blocks. Ours is an RDF statement graph: the nodes are entities and the edges are typed predicates with provenance and a review status. Theirs is easier to write into; ours is the one you can interrogate, diff, and cite." .

